{{Infobox street | name = Amager Boulevard | native_name = | image = Amager Vest, Copenhagen, Denmark - panoramio (11).jpg | image_size = 320px | caption = Amager Boulevard with [[Stadsgreven]] to th left as seen from Hotel Tadison Blue Scandinavia | former_names = | postal_code = 2300 | length_m = 1260 | width = | location = [[Amager]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] | coordinates = {{coord|55|41|6|N|12|34|10.08|E}} }} [[Image:Amager Vest, Copenhagen, Denmark - panoramio (11).jpg|thumb|300px|Amager Boulevard with [[Stadsgreven]] to th left as seen from Hotel Tadison Blue Scandinavia]] '''Amager Boulevard''' is a street on [[Amager]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It It begins at [[Langebro|Langebro Bridge]] and initially follows [[Stadsgraven]] east to a Y-junction from where it continues inland to [[Amagerbrogade]] while the street '''Ved Stadsgraven''' contintues along the water to the [[Christmas Møllers Plads]].
==History== [[File:Amager Boulevard 1915.jpg|thumb|200px|Amager Boulevard seen from Langebro in 1915]] The southernmost portion of [[Christianshavns Enveloppe]], a low rampart in front of [[Christianshavns Vold]] and [[Stadsgraven]], was formerly located at the site where Amager Boulevard runs today. In front of it was a shallow-watered area. Amager's shoreline was then located approximately where Artillerivej runs today. In the 1880s, it was decided to build a new arsenal at the site as a replacement for [[Christian IV's Arsenal]] on [[Slotsholmen]] which had become too small. The southernmost portion of Christianshavns Enveloppe was removed and the area reclaimed and New Arsenal (Ny Tøjhus) was inaugurated in 1888. It was joined by the Army's Rifle Gactory in 1991 and the Army's Technical Corps in 1909.
Amager Boulevard was constructed in 1906-07. When the new [[Langebro]] was constructed in 1954, Amager Boulevard was connected directly to it by a ramp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianshavnernet.dk/RendezVous_Christianshavn/Minedepotet.html|title=Søminedepotet|language=Danish|website=christianshavnernet.dk|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref>
==Notable buildings and residents== [[File:Statens Serum Institut hovedbygning.JPG|thumb|200px|The Serum Institute's old main building]] Langebrohus (No. 2) is from 1906 and was designed by [[Thorvald Gundestrup]] who also designed several other large properties that line [[Islands Brygge]].
Then follows the headquarters of the IT company [[SimCorp]] (Weidekampsgade 16), the labour union HK (Weidekampsgade 8),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkark.dk/building.aspx?buildingid=3238|title=HK Danmark, København|language=Danish|website=arkark.dk|accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref> KL and [[Deloitte]] which are all part of the New Arsenal redevelopment and entered from the other side of the block..
The Radisson Blu Scandinavia Hotel (No, 70) is from 1973. There are plans to extend it with 10 extra floors. [[Statens Serum Institut]] (No, 80). The oldest of its buildings is from 1902 and was designed by [[Andreas Clemmensen]]. Kvinderegensen (No. 110) is from 1932 which was originally reserved for female students. The building was designed by [[Helge Bojsen-Møller]] and the rooms were designed by [[Rigmor Andersen]]. The Norwegian House (No. 111) is a meetingplace for Norwegians in Copenhagen. It is operated by the [[Association of Norwegians in Denmark]], an organisation founded in 1863. The building is from
[[Mønten Kollegium]] (No. 115 was built for the [[Royal Mint (Denmark)|Royal Mint]] in 1923. The Historicist building was designed by [[Martin Borch]]. The Royal Mint moved to [[Vrøndby]] in 1975 and the building is now owned by [[Mikael Goldschmidt Holding|Mikael Goldschmidt Ejendomme]] and has been converted into youth housing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgh.dk/subpages/top/news/articles/n210212.php|title=150 nye ungdomsboliger og 23 erhvervslejemål midt i København|language=Danish|publisher=M. Goldschmidt Holding|accessdate=2013-04-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426225218/http://mgh.dk/subpages/top/news/articles/n210212.php|archive-date=2012-04-26|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Mp. 118, a residential building called Møllegården, is also from 1923 and was designed by [[Povl Baumann]].
