{{Infobox building | name = Schalun Castle | native_name = Burg Schalun {{de icon}} | alternate_names = Ruine Schalun, Wildschloss | image = | map_type = | altitude = | building_type = Ruined [[castle]] | ren_cost = | location = [[Vaduz]], [[Liechtenstein]] | address = | client = | owner = [[Municipalities of Liechtenstein|Municipality]] of [[Vaduz]] | coordinates = {{coord|47.1509|9.5336|type:landmark_region:LI|display=inline,title}} | start_date = built around the end of the 12th century, first written record from 1237 | height = | diameter = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = | floor_area = }}
'''Schalun Castle''' ([[German language|German]] ''Burg Schalun'' or ''Ruine Schalun''), also known [[Colloquialism|colloquially]] as '''Wildschloss''' ("Castle in the wild"), is a castle ruin located in the [[Municipalities of Liechtenstein|municipality]] of [[Vaduz]], [[Liechtenstein]]. It lies in the mountains, roughly 1 kilometer to the northeast from the town centre of [[Vaduz]], the capital of Liechtenstein. It is freely open to tourists and accessible by foot or mountain bike via a local footpath.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tourismus.li/en/culture-cuisine/places-of-cultural-interest/cultural-places-of-historical-interest/Wildschloss.html |title=Liechtenstein : The Official Tourism Site - Culture & Cuisine - Places of historical interest : The Wildschloss (Schalun Castle) |date=2013-01-05 |accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christian-tanner.com/burgruinen/burgen-von-f%C3%BCrstentum-liechtenstein/burg-schalun-wildschloss-vaduz/ |title=Photos of Schalun Castle |date=2013-01-05 |accessdate=2013-01-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212083552/http://www.christian-tanner.com/burgruinen/burgen-von-f%C3%BCrstentum-liechtenstein/burg-schalun-wildschloss-vaduz/ |archivedate=2013-02-12 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://picasaweb.google.com/100236546751027306466/LichtensteinBurgen#5739337084885025842 |title=A photo of the castle on Picasaweb.google.com |date=2013-01-05 |accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref> Schalun Castle is one of the five existing castles in Liechtenstein and one of the three ruined ones in the country.
==History== The castle was constructed probably around the end of the 12th century. The first written record about the castle comes from 1237. In it, it was also first referred to by name, as "Schalun". Archeological digs made in recent decades have revealed only small amounts of artefacts from the medieval and early modern period, suggesting that the castle might have been cleared and burned down at a later point in its history.
In the 18th century, the castle came into the possession of the then Prince Regnant of [[Liechtenstein]]. The ownership of the castle ruin was handed over to the [[Municipalities of Liechtenstein|Municipality]] of [[Vaduz]] in 1933.
Today, the best preserved parts of the castle are its grand hall and the remaining section of its keep.<ref>{{cite book |author=Cornelia Herrmann |title=''Die Kunstdenkmäler des Fürstentums Liechtenstein. Das Oberland.'' In: Gesellschaft für Schweizerische Kunstgeschichte GSK: ''Die Kunstdenkmäler der Schweiz.'' Bern 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-906131-85-6}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burgenwelt.org/liechtenstein/schalun/object.php |title=Schalun Castle on Burgenwelt.de (in German) |date=2016-01-22 |accessdate=2016-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burgenwelt.org/liechtenstein/schalun/object.php#grundriss |title=Ground plan of Schalun Castle on Burgenwelt.de (in German) |date=2016-01-22 |accessdate=2016-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://merlinandrebecca.blogspot.com/2011/08/castle-hunting-schloss-valduz.html |title=Article about Vaduz Castle and Schalun castle (includes images of both) |date=2011-08-18 |accessdate=2013-04-14}}</ref>
